<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-03-21T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-03-21T19:00:00-05:00" n="55" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d55">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/3–1451: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the United States Deputy Representative on the North Atlantic
                                    Council</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SCM1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Spofford</hi></persName>), <hi rend="italic">at London</hi><note n="1" xml:id="d55fn1">
                                    <persName corresp="#p_KRB1">Knight</persName> drafted this
                                    telegram and cleared it with Colonel <persName corresp="#p_BCRE1">Beebe</persName> (Defense) and, in
                                    substance, with <persName corresp="#p_BJCH1">Bonbright</persName>.</note>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-03-21T19:00:00-05:00">March
                                        21, 1951—7 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <gloss target="#t_Todep1">Todep</gloss> 314. We (State and Defense)
                                consider polit “guidance” wld be accepted as “direction” and hence
                                consider them synonymous. We also consider that civilian control of
                                natl policy in peace time is unquestioned. We believe question of
                                guidance versus direction to be essentially one of semantics. You
                                might usefully refer to Para 15 Part one of <gloss target="#t_DC1">DC</gloss> 24/3<note n="2" xml:id="d55fn2">See footnote 6, <ref target="#pg_70">p. 70</ref>.</note> which states that
                                council Deputies as only higher <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> polit body in continuous session shld be channel
                                through which polit guidance to mil agencies is funnelled, and point
                                out that language used in this doc was approved by both Defense
                                Comite and Council. You cld also refer to Appeal Provisions in Para
                                16 Part one <gloss target="#t_DC1">DC</gloss> 24/3 which clearly
                                indicate that guidance synonymous with direction, at least for
                                purposes this doc, as otherwise there wld be no need for appeal.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>